 presence directly.","file":"/Users/greggcochran/dev/terminal-stampede/bin/stampede-monitor.sh","line":41,"recommendation":"If `commanders/` is the source of truth, add a direct directory check or fallback before relying on `fleet.json`."},{"severity":"major","title":"Commander nested status is read from swarm-state.json, but not all requested fields are shown verbatim","detail":"For each commander, it reads `progress_dir/swarm-state.json` and displays phase, launch counts, atoms received, and children failed via telemetry fallbacks. However, the output is synthesized (`squads ...`, `workers ...`, `run ... done ... fail ...`, `hb ...`) rather than explicitly showing `squad_leads_launched/target`, `workers_launched/target`, `atoms_received`, `children_failed` labels.","file":"/Users/greggcochran/dev/terminal-stampede/bin/stampede-monitor.sh","line":145,"recommendation":"If exact field visibility matters, print the canonical keys/labels directly from swarm-state.json."},{"severity":"major","title":"No child-agents.jsonl tailing or JSONL-derived live counts","detail":"The monitor does not read `commanders/{id}/child-agents.jsonl`; there is no tailing, record counting, or malformed-line tolerance logic for that file. Live commander status comes from `swarm-state.json` plus tmux pane state.","file":"/Users/greggcochran/dev/terminal-stampede/bin/stampede-monitor.sh","line":145,"recommendation":"Add a JSONL reader that skips malformed trailing lines and derives recent launches/completions from `child-agents.jsonl` if that telemetry is required."},{"severity":"minor","title":"Heartbeat age is shown, but there is no dedicated Agent Pulse section or explicit stuck threshold display","detail":"The commander line includes `hb <age>s` from `last_heartbeat_at` (fallback `updated_at`), but there is no separate “Agent Pulse” section or explicit `stuck >N seconds` commander-pane detection. Stuck detection is only a generic claimed-file age warning at 120s.","file":"/Users/greggcochran/dev/terminal-stampede/bin/stampede-monitor.sh","line":167,"recommendation":"Add a dedicated per-commander pulse/stall panel using `last_heartbeat_at` and a visible threshold indicator."},{"severity":"major","title":"Commander pane death is only inferred indirectly; no commander-specific blocked/stuck marking","detail":"If a commander pane dies, the monitor’s tmux pane census marks the pane `dead`, and orphan recovery may return stale claimed tasks when no live agents remain. But there is no commander-specific blocked/stuck state tied to pane death, and the recovery path is task-centric rather than spawning a replacement commander.","file":"/Users/greggcochran/dev/terminal-stampede/bin/stampede-monitor.sh","line":218,"recommendation":"On dead commander panes, surface an explicit commander stuck/blocked status and decide whether launcher recovery should respawn or preserve partial state."},{"severity":"minor","title":"Run classification uses state.json only for total_tasks/repo_path, not metaswarm profile","detail":"`state.json` is read for `total_tasks` and `repo_path`, but not to determine metaswarm vs standard mode. That decision comes from `fleet.json`/`collab`, so `state.json` profile is not used here.","file":"/Users/greggcochran/dev/terminal-stampede/bin/stampede-monitor.sh","line":69,"recommendation":"If run profile belongs in state.json, consult it directly to avoid split-brain classification."},{"severity":"info","title":"Path assumptions are fairly fixed but still mostly run-id scoped","detail":"The monitor assumes `.stampede/$RUN_ID`, `$HOME/.stampede/$RUN_ID`, or `$HOME/.copilot/stampede/$RUN_ID`, plus fixed subpaths like `fleet.json`, `state.json`, `queue/`, `claimed/`, `results/`, and `commanders/<id>/swarm-state.json`. This is run-id scoped, but any alternate layout will break.","file":"/Users/greggcochran/dev/terminal-stampede/bin/stampede-monitor.sh","line":6,"recommendation":"Parameterize the base layout or discover paths from state metadata if arbitrary run layouts must be supported."}],"blockers_count":0,"summary":"Nested metaswarm rendering exists, but it is driven by fleet.json/collab rather than commander-directory discovery. Commander rows do read swarm-state.json and show heartbeat age and aggregated counts, but there is no child-agents.jsonl tail/count logic, no explicit Agent Pulse section, and no commander-specific stuck/blocked state on pane death. Recovery is task-oriented (stale claim rollback) and does not respawn dead commanders. state.json is used for totals/repo path, not metaswarm detection."}{"area":"commander-manifests","findings":[{"severity":"major","title":"swarm-state task_id sample is misleading/ambiguous","detail":"The documented `swarm-state.json` shape shows `task_id: \"commander-001\"`, which reads like a commander id, not the claimed task id. This can confuse an LLM about whether `task_id` should be the queue task id or commander id.","file":"/Users/greggcochran/dev/terminal-stampede/agents/stampede-commander.agent.md","line":75,"recommendation":"Change the example to a real claimed task id and explicitly say `task_id` is the claimed queue task id."},{"severity":"minor","title":"child-agents.jsonl schema is only example-based","detail":"The doc gives sample JSONL records, but not a full required schema per event. Fields like `launch_requested` vs `launch_started` vs `completed` are not clearly enumerated, so field presence can be under-specified.","file":"/Users/greggcochran/dev/terminal-stampede/agents/stampede-commander.agent.md","line":132,"recommendation":"Add a compact per-event field table (required/optional) for `launch_requested`, `launch_started`, `completed`, and any update events."},{"severity":"major","title":"Launcher and agent doc differ on state/manifest contract fields","detail":"The launcher’s metaswarm contract includes `telemetry_contract` and `collab` in the generated commander state, plus `state_file`, `child_ledger`, and `sub_agent_ledger` aliases. Those f